<DOC><DOCNO> AP891102-0273 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1248EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-US-JapanCable     11-02 0287</FIRST><SECOND>PM-US-Japan Cable,0297</SECOND><HEAD>Trans-Pacific Cable Gets OK</HEAD><DATELINE>VANCOUVER, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Pacific Telecom Cable Inc. receivedfinal federal approval to install the western end of the firstdigital fiber-optic cable that will stretch directly from theUnited States to Japan.   Pacific Telecom Cable, a majority-owned subsidiary of PacificTelecom Inc., said Wednesday it received a final license from theFederal Communications Commission. It had received a conditionalFCC license in April 1987.   The license will enable the company to link Pacific City, Ore.and Seward, Alaska with the international fiber-optic cable networkby the target date of December 1990, company President DennisElliott said.   The cable project is a joint venture between Pacific TelecomCable of the United States, International Digital CommunicationsInc. of Japan and Cable and Wireless PLC of the United Kingdom.Pacific Telecom owns the U.S. portion of the project.   The 5,200-mile project is the largest fiber-optic cable networkauthorized for the Pacific Ocean region and the first to providedirect service between the United States and Japan, the companysaid. Currently, telephone services are routed through Hawaii.   The network will link the U.S. domestic digital network,trans-Atlantic fiber optic cables, and fiber optic networks servingJapan, Asia and the Pacific Rim.   The cable can carry up to 85,000 telephone conversationssimultaneously on 17,010 circuits.   The increase in capacity will allow users to place calls easierand the digital fiber-optic materials will make the connectionsclearer, said Stephen E. Lovas, Pacific Telecom Cablevice-president of sales and marketing.   The system will also provide the first digital fiber-optic linkbetween Alaska and the rest of the U.S. mainland through anunderwater branching unit 700 miles south of Seward. Currently,analog satellite systems are used.</TEXT></DOC>